\napproximately to the mean density at the cluster virial radius. The same\ncorrelation holds for galaxies more than two virial radii from the cluster\ncentre. We conclude that environmental influences on galaxy properties are not\nrestricted to cluster cores, but are effective in all groups where the density\nexceeds this critical value. The present day abundance of such systems, and the\nstrong evolution of this abundance, makes it likely that hierarchical growth of\nstructure plays a significant role in decreasing the global average star\nformation rate. Finally, the low star formation rates well beyond the\nvirialised cluster rule out severe physical processes, such as ram pressure\nstripping of disk gas, as being completely responsible for the variations in\ngalaxy properties with environment.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 20 Mar 2002 13:06:00 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 21 Mar 2002 09:58:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-03-10"}
