{"id":"quant-ph/0203100","submitter":"Karen Milena Fonseca Romero","authors":"K.M. Fonseca-Romero, G. Useche-Laverde, F. Torres-Ardila","title":"Optimal Control of One-Qubit Gates","comments":"5 pages","journal-ref":"K M Fonseca Romero et al J. Phys. A: Math. Gen. 36 841 (2003)","doi":"10.1088/0305-4470/36/3/317","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We consider the problem of carrying an initial Bloch vector to a final Bloch\nvector in a specified amount of time under the action of three control fields\n(a vector control field). We show that this control problem is solvable and\ntherefore it is possible to optimize the control. We choose the physically\nmotivated criteria of minimum energy spent in the control, minimum magnitude of\nthe rate of change of the control and a combination of both. We find exact\nanalytical solutions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 20 Mar 2002 14:14:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-02-21"}
{"id":"quant-ph/0203101","submitter":"Luigi Solombrino","authors":"L. Solombrino","title":"Weak pseudo-Hermiticity and antilinear commutant","comments":"9 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1063/1.1504485","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We inquire into some properties of diagonalizable pseudo-Hermitian operators,\nshowing that their definition can be relaxed and that the pseudo-Hermiticity\nproperty is strictly connected with the existence of an antilinear symmetry.\nThis result is then illustrated by considering the particular case of the\ncomplex Morse potential.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 20 Mar 2002 15:38:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
